From #6936

Version 1.4.0-insider, Commit 531a56f772fc33ec88910328b88f4dbd7ae5df43, Date 2016-07-28T16:52:53.252Z
Add this to glob.test.ts:

``` typescript
         p = '{**/package.json,**/project.json}';
         assert(glob.match(p, 'package.json'));
         assert(glob.match(p, '/package.json'));
         assert(!glob.match(p, 'xpackage.json'));
         assert(!glob.match(p, '/xpackage.json'));
```

Fails at the last assert.

- VSCode Version: 1.3.1
- OS Version: Windows 8.1

Steps to Reproduce:
- Create a normal JS object (using ES6 syntax here):

```
class randomClass {
  constructor () {
    let self = this;
    this.variable = null;
    self.variable = 'lol';
  }
}
```
- Put the cursor in "variable" and press F12 (or click any of the definition stuff in the right-click menu - peek, go, etc.). Nothing happens, not even the tooltip shows anything.
- Expected behavior:
  VS Code should either:
  - Show a list of the found definitions in the command palette (Control+Shift+P) and when you scroll through them using the arrow keys the cursor/screen should scroll to where that definition is found (mimics Sublime's behavior which is great)
  - Show a list like in VS2015 when you click "Show all references" in a C# project. Same behavior: Click and it takes you where that definition is found.

Basically, there should be a way to find out where does a variable come from. A search works, or Control+D, but that way you can't go forward/backwards, whereas with the first proposed option you can do so :)

- VSCode Version: Version 1.3.1 (1.3.1)
- OS Version: OS X El Capitan 10.11.6

Steps to Reproduce:
1. This Javascript code does not highlight properly:

```
for (i = 0; i<len ; i++) {
  if (foo) {
    bar = true 
    break 
  }
}
```
1. Changing this part `i<len ;` to at least `i< len;` fixes the bug:

```
for (i = 0; i< len; i++) {
  if (foo) {
    bar = true 
    break 
  }
}
```

Problem seems only to occur with "lower than" operator alone when no space are around the operator and the next semicolon is separated by a space.

PS: that's not the way I would normally format it :)
Found this "for loop" format style in a popular external library.
